==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|ēvapōrātus}}, perfect passive participle of {{m|la|ēvapōrō||evaporate}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ɪˈvæpəɹeɪt/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-evaporate.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|evaporat}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive}} to [[transition]] from a [[liquid]] state into a [[gaseous]] state
# {{lb|en|transitive}} to expel moisture from (usually by means of artificial heat), leaving the solid portion
#: ''to '''evaporate''' apples''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} to give vent to; to dissipate
#* Sir H. Wotton
#*: My lord of Essex '''evaporated''' his thoughts in a sonnet.
# {{lb|en|figuratively}} to [[disappear]]; to escape or pass off without effect
#* Francis Bacon
#*: To give moderate liberty for griefs and discontents to '''evaporate''' {{...}} is a safe way.
#* {{quote-journal
|date=March 2, 2011
|author=Chris Whyatt
|title=Arsenal 5 - 0 Leyton Orient
|work=BBC
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/9405635.stm
|page=
|passage=The hosts initially looked like they lacked a spring in their step, but fears of further agony '''evaporated''' in the seventh minute with a goal of typical Arsenal quality.}}

